{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "By enabling decentralized decision-making and enhancing coordination among various agents, MAS have contributed significantly to handling complexities in the manufacturing system [5].However, there are still challenges in MAS frameworks in manufacturing.",
    "While agents in MAS can automate processes and make decisions, their ability to adapt to new formats or specifications is limited, leading to increased downtime.",
    "1 Jonghan Lim and Ilya Kovalenko are with the Department of Industrial and Manufacturing and the Department of Mechanical Engineering, Pennsylvania State University, State College, USA (e-mail: {jxl567; iqk5135}@psu.edu).2 Birgit Vogel-Heuser is with the Institute of Automation and Information Systems, Technical University of Munich, Munich, Germany (e-mail: vogelheuser@tum.de).Thus, a challenge includes the limited ability of agents to dynamically adapt to new information including product specifications (RCh1).",
    "Another challenge lies in processing unstructured textual data.",
    "Textual data is crucial because it is more expressive than numerical data, offering vast knowledge that is currently underutilized in manufacturing, where structured data fails to include varied influencing factors [6]."
  ],
